Here’s a clear, step-by-step guide to complete your
Cloud Monitoring: Qwik Start Lab (Activity 8) 👇

✅ Step-by-Step Procedure
🔹 Step 1: Start Lab & Login
Click Start Lab
Open Google Cloud Console
Login using:
Username (given)
Password (given)
Accept terms → Skip recovery options
🔹 Step 2: Activate Cloud Shell
Click Activate Cloud Shell (top-right)
Click Continue → Authorize
🔹 Step 3: Set Region & Zone

Run these commands:

gcloud config set compute/zone "ZONE"
export ZONE=$(gcloud config get compute/zone)

gcloud config set compute/region "REGION"
export REGION=$(gcloud config get compute/region)
🔹 Step 4: Create VM Instance
Go to Compute Engine → VM Instances
Click Create Instance
Enter details:
Field	Value
Name	lamp-1-vm
Region	Given REGION
Zone	Given ZONE
Series	E2
Machine Type	e2-medium
Click OS and Storage
Select Debian GNU/Linux 12
Click Networking
Enable Allow HTTP traffic
Click Create

✅ Wait until green tick appears

🔹 Step 5: Install Apache Web Server
Click SSH for lamp-1-vm
Run commands:
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install apache2 php7.0
sudo service apache2 restart

👉 If php7.0 fails:

sudo apt-get install apache2 php5
🔹 Step 6: Verify Web Server
Go back to VM list
Click External IP
You should see:
👉 Apache default page
🔹 Step 7: Open Cloud Monitoring
Go to:
Navigation Menu → Monitoring
Monitoring workspace auto-creates
🔹 Step 8: Install Monitoring & Logging Agents
Run in SSH:
curl -sSO https://dl.google.com/cloudagents/add-google-cloud-ops-agent-repo.sh
sudo bash add-google-cloud-ops-agent-repo.sh --also-install

👉 Press Y if asked

Check status:

sudo systemctl status google-cloud-ops-agent"*"

Press q to exit

🔹 Step 9: Create Uptime Check
Go to Monitoring → Uptime checks
Click Create Uptime Check
Enter:
Field	Value
Protocol	HTTP
Resource Type	URL
Hostname	External IP of VM
Frequency	1 minute
Click Continue → Continue → Continue
Name: Lamp Uptime Check
Click Test → Create
🔹 Step 10: Create Alerting Policy
Go to Monitoring → Alerting
Click + Create Policy
Configure Metric:
Click Select Metric
Search: Network traffic

Choose:

VM instance → Interface → Network traffic
Click Next
Set Condition:
Threshold: Above
Value: 500
Retest window: 1 min
Click Next
Add Notification (Email):
Click Manage Notification Channels
Add:
Email address
Display name
Save
Refresh → Select your email
Final:
Alert Name: Inbound Traffic Alert
Click Create Policy
🔹 Step 11: Create Dashboard
Go to Monitoring → Dashboards
Click Create Dashboard
Name:
👉 Cloud Monitoring LAMP Dashboard
Add Chart 1 (CPU):
Click Add Widget → Line
Title: CPU Load

Metric:

VM instance → CPU → CPU load (1m)
Add Chart 2 (Packets):
Click Add Widget
Title: Received Packets

Metric:

VM instance → Received packets
🔹 Step 12: View Logs
Go to:
Navigation → Logging → Logs Explorer
Select:
Resource: VM Instance
Instance: lamp-1-vm
🔹 Step 13: Test Logs (Stop & Start VM)
Stop VM:
Go to Compute Engine
Click 3 dots → Stop
Start VM:
Click Start

👉 Watch logs update in real time

🔹 Step 14: Check Uptime & Alerts
Go to Monitoring → Uptime Checks
Open Lamp Uptime Check

👉 Initially may show failed, wait 2–5 minutes

Check Alerts:
Go to Monitoring → Alerting
See incidents

📧 Check your email → alert received
